|date=19 August 1914 |title=Our Booking-Office. (By Mr Punch's Staff of Learned Clerks)\n |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/26969/26969-h/26969-h.htm |magazine=Punch}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|title=Dornford Yates |last= Smithers |first=AJ |publisher=[[Hodder & Stoughton|Hodder and Stoughton]] |year=1982 |location=London |isbn=0 340 27547 2}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|title=Clubland Heroes |last= Usborne |first=Richard |publisher=Barrie & Jenkins |year=1974 |location=London |isbn=0 214 20012 4}}\n\n[[Category:1914 short story collections]]\n[[Category:Ward Lock & Co books]]\n[[Category:Short story collections by Dornford Yates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1914 short story collection by Dornford Yates}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = The Brother of Daphne\n| image        = The Brother of Daphne 1942 reprint.jpg\n| caption      = 1942 Ward Lock reprint\n| author       = [[Dornford Yates]]\n| genre        =\n| publisher    = [[Ward Lock & Co]]<ref name=\"BLcat\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=003995523&con_lng=eng |title=British Library Item details |website=primocat.bl.uk |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n| release_date = 1914<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| media_type   = Print \n| pages        = 304<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = [[The Courts of Idleness]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Brother of Daphne''''' is a 1914 collection of comic short stories by the English author [[Dornford Yates]] (Cecil William Mercer), his first published book. It was in these stories that Yates first introduced the group of characters that featured in many of his future works: Bertram ('Berry') Pleydell, his wife and cousin Daphne Pleydell, Daphne's brother Boy Pleydell, another cousin Jonathan ('Jonah') Mansell, and Jonah's younger sister Jill Mansell.  The group of five - Berry, Daphne, Boy, Jonah and Jill - later came to be known collectively as 'Berry and Co'.{{sfn|Usborne|1974|pp=28-29}}\n\n== Background ==\n\nThe short stories in the collection were originally published in ''[[The Windsor Magazine]]'',{{sfn|Smithers|1982|loc=Appendix I}} their publication in book form having been suggested to Mercer by the ''Windsor'''s editor Arthur Hutchinson.{{sfn|Smithers|1982|p=78}}\n\n== Chapters == \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chapter Number\n! scope=\"col\" | Book Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Windsor Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Windsor Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Windsor Volume\n! scope=\"col\" | Windsor Issue\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| Punch And Judy\n| Punch And Judy\n| October 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 202\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| Clothes And The Man\n| There Is A Tide\n| August 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 224\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| When It Was Dark\n| A Drive In The Dark\n| November 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 203\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| Adam And New Year's Eve\n| Fair Exchange\n| January 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 229\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| The Judgement of Paris\n| The Judgement of Paris\n| June 1914\n| XL\n| 234\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| Which To Adore\n| Which To Adore\n| March 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 231\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| Every Picture Tells A Story\n| Every Picture Tells A Story\n| July 1914\n| XL\n| 235\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| The Busy Beers\n| Busy Bees\n| September 1911\n| XXXIV\n| 201\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| A Point Of Honour\n| A Point Of Honour\n| October 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 226\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| Pride Goeth Before\n| Pride Goeth Before\n| April 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 232\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| The Love Scene\n| The Love Scene\n| September 1913\n| XXXVIII\n| 225\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| The Order Of The Bath\n| The Order Of The Bath\n| May 1914\n| XXXIX\n| 233\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |